Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, it looks like white’s queen on b6 is attacking both of black’s rooks along the key diagonal (b6–c7–d8). (Note that the rook on c7 is defended by the black king on b8 but the rook on d8 is hanging.) One good idea is to reposition the rook on d8 so that the two rooks end up helping each other. For example, by playing

  d8c8

the rook on d8 moves along the 8th rank to c8, thereby joining the rook already on c7 on the same file. Now if white tries to grab one of them (say by capturing on c7), black will be able to recapture (for instance, Rxc7) and win the white queen for a rook—a trade white will not allow. 

So, I will play:

make_move d8c8

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Failed to make move: illegal uci: 'd8c8' in 1k1r4/2r4p/pQ2p3/6P1/Pp3P2/7B/1K6/2R5 b - - 0 38

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

The black king on b8 is currently in check from white’s queen on b6 along the b‐file (with b7 empty between them). In order to get out of check, black must either move the king or block the check. (There’s no possibility to capture the queen.)

If Black moves the king, the only safe option is Kb8→a8. However, that leaves the rook on c7 undefended along the b6–c7 diagonal, so White could capture on c7 next, winning a rook for a queen.

A better solution is to block the check. The only square between b6 and b8 is b7. The rook sitting on c7 can move horizontally one square from c7 to b7, interposing the check. (Note that if White subsequently takes the rook on b7 with Qxb7, Black can recapture with the king, and then Black will have exchanged a rook for White’s queen—which is clearly not in White’s interest.)

Therefore, I will play:

make_move c7b7

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I’m considering an active line with our queen. Our queen is currently on d6, and one promising candidate is to move it diagonally to c5. That move puts the white king (on c2) in check along the c‐file while keeping our queen safely out of immediate reach (it won’t be adjacent to the white king, nor is it on a square accessible to the white bishop on a2).

To explain briefly:
• Our queen on d6 can legally slide diagonally to c5.
• On c5 the queen gives a direct check along the c‐file down to white’s king on c2.
• None of white’s pieces (the pawn on a5, pawn on g5, or bishop on a2) can immediately capture our queen on c5.

Thus, I’ll complete my turn with the move “d6c5.”

make_move d6c5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current position, I believe the best plan is to bring my king closer to support the pawn before advancing it. If I pushed the pawn from b4 to b3 immediately, it would sit unprotected and the white king on c2 could capture it on b3 (since b3 would be adjacent to white king).

Instead, I want to move my king from c5 to c4. With the king on c4, it will protect the crucial square b3. Then, once I advance the pawn by playing b4b3, the white king will not be able to capture it because b3 will be guarded by my king (remember that kings cannot move into squares adjacent to the opposing king). This is the classic technique of escorting a passed pawn in a king-and-pawn versus king endgame.

So, my move is:

make_move c5c4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, here’s one line of reasoning from Black’s perspective:

• Black’s material is very limited (only a king plus six pawns), so counterplay must come entirely from pawn advances and king safety.
• The pawn on g7 is still on its original square. Pushing it to g6 not only gives the king additional “luft” (an escape square), but also begins to mobilize Black’s kingside pawn majority.
• Other pawn moves (like advancing b5, c5, or f5) are likely less urgent, and moving the king without easing the cramped nature of Black’s position might allow White more energetic checks.
  
Thus, a move like “g7g6” appears to be a sensible, consolidating strategy that improves Black’s position immediately. 

make_move g7g6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

After reviewing the board, one promising option is to improve king safety. In the current position the black pieces are limited – with king on g8 and three pawns (on a6, g4, and a2) – and the g4 pawn is already under the white queen’s attack along the fourth rank. Moving a pawn (like g4→g3) would only delay its capture, while the a6 and a2 pawns are essentially blocked. 

The best resource appears to be repositioning the king. From g8, the legal king moves are to f8, f7, or g7. Notably, moving to g7 would align the king vertically with the white queen if it captures on g4 (since the queen on h4 controls the h–file and moving horizontally from there can bring it to an aligned file with the king on g7). In contrast, shifting the king to f8 avoids such immediate alignment, keeping the king slightly tucked away on the back rank.

Therefore, I will move my king from g8 to f8.

Action: make_move g8f8

• The Black pawn on a2 cannot advance because its forward square (a1) is blocked by the White knight, and it has no diagonal capture available (since b1 is empty).
• That leaves the Black king on d7. Its potential king moves (one square in any direction) must avoid entering squares attacked by White. Checking the vicinity:
  – From d7, the king can go to:
   • d8 (rank8, file d)
   • e8 (rank8, file e)
   • c7 (rank7, file c)
   • e7 (rank7, file e)
The other neighboring squares (like c8, d6, c6, or e6) fall on squares controlled by the White queen on a6 (remember that from a6 the queen commands the entire 6th rank and the diagonal through b7, c8, etc.).

All four listed moves appear legal and safe from immediate queen checks or interference from other White pieces. With Black in a very delicate material situation, the king’s safety is paramount. Moving the king from d7 to e7 (notation: d7e7) seems a reasonable choice, keeping it on a relatively central and secure square while retaining maximum mobility.

make_move d7e7

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the diagram’s coordinates (with the top row being rank 8 and the bottom row rank 1), here is a summary of the position:

• Black has only a king on c7 and a pawn on a2.
• White has two pawns (on a5 and b5), a queen on f6, a knight on c2, and the king on g4.

Looking at Black’s resources, the pawn on a2 can move forward one square (to a1) and promote—but note that white’s knight on c2 has a legal jump to a1 (since from c2 the knight can go to a1), immediately capturing any promoted piece. That makes a pawn move less attractive.

Thus, Black’s only real hope is to safely reposition the king. From c7 the king’s legal moves (ignoring any move that would step into an attacked square) are:
  • c7–b8
  • c7–c8
  • c7–b7
  • c7–d7

A quick look at the threats shows that moving toward the “back rank” is a reasonable defensive choice. For example, a move to b8 places the king farther from the action and avoids the white queen’s – which on f6 controls horizontally (rank 6) plus the two main diagonals that include d8 and a1. Also, none of white’s pieces (the queen, knight, or pawns) can immediately target b8.

Therefore, a good candidate move for Black is to shift the king from c7 to b8. In UCI notation that move is written as:

make_move c7b8

I’ll now play that move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the move: make_move e4f2

Here's my reasoning:

On the board, my knight currently sits on e4 and by moving it to f2 you capture White’s pawn on f2. More importantly, sitting on f2 the knight immediately threatens to jump to d1 (a legal knight move from f2) on the next move, which would attack White’s queen on d1. This forces White to react. In many positions, such a move creates serious tactical headaches for the opponent, as it either wins material or forces awkward king moves.

So I choose e4f2.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

It turns out that the move d8d5 doesn’t address the immediate problem: your king on c8 is currently in check along the open c‑file from White’s queen on c3. (Recall that the squares between c3 and c8—namely c4, c5, c6, and c7—are empty.) When in check, you must either capture the checking piece, interpose a piece between the checking piece and your king, or move your king.

In this position no black piece can capture the white queen on c3, and none can interpose on the c‑file (the dark‑squared bishop on f8 is blocked by your pawn on e7, and your other pieces cannot reach one of the blocking squares on c4–c7). The only available way to respond is to move your king.

Looking at King c8’s adjacent squares:
 • b8 is empty and appears to be safe.
 • d7 is also an option.
 • Other adjacent squares are either occupied by your own pawn(s) (for example, b7) or remain in the line of the queen.

I will choose to move the king to b8. So my move is: 
 make_move c8b8

Your turn!

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play  Qc3  (i.e. move the queen from c2 to c3, giving check).

To explain briefly: by moving the queen from c2 to c3, the queen lands on a square adjacent to the black king (on d3), so if White’s king (currently on a3) tries to capture the queen that move would put it next to the black king – an illegal situation. Although White’s king still has some flight squares (such as a2 or a4), this check forces White to move and keeps up the pressure while Black retains a decisive material advantage.

So, my move is: make_move c2c3

  Rank3: ⭘ ⭘ ♛ ♚ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ 
  Rank2: ♔ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ 
  Rank1: ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ 

we note that Black’s important pieces lie on:
 • King at d3 
 • Queen at c3 
 • Pawns at a7, b7, c7, g7, and h7

White has only the king on a2.

In king‐and‐queen versus king endings the standard plan is to use your king to “shoulder” the enemy king while the queen delivers the decisive check. Here the White monarch on a2 has very few escape squares (its surrounding squares are: a1, a3, b1, b2, and b3). For instance, if Black could safely cover the squares b1, b2, and b3, a checking move with the queen (for example to b2) would be mate because then the White king would be trapped (even though a queen giving check must not be captured unless it is defended).

A very natural candidate is to move the Black king from d3 to c2. In UCI notation that move is “d3c2.” Notice that with the Black king on c2 it now controls b1, b2, and b3—the three squares immediately adjacent to the White king (which sits on a2). This move does not give immediate check, but it very forcefully restricts the White king’s options. After Black’s King lands on c2, whatever square White’s king chooses (it will be forced to either a1 or a3, since b1, b2, and b3 are now ruled out), Black will have the decisive resource of a queen check (for example, Qb2 becomes especially punishing because if White tries to capture the queen it would be moving into the zone controlled by your king).

Thus, as Black I will choose to improve my king’s position with:

 make_move d3c2

I now commit to that move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1...f7f5, advancing the pawn from f7 to f5. 

This move does two things. First, it protects the knight on e4 – now if White’s queen on d5 tries to capture that knight (moving Qxe4), the pawn on f5 recaptures (f5xe4), trapping the queen on an attacked square. Second, although White's queen still eyes the bishop on d6, capturing it immediately (Qxd6) is a trap since Black can reply with c7xd6 and win the queen. 

So I answer: make_move f7f5

In our current position the knight sits on f6, and moving it to d5 serves several purposes. From d5 the knight eyes critical central squares and even comes into contact with the white pawn on b4, while it’s safely backed by Black’s pawn on c6 (which can capture on d5 if white chooses to trade). This keeps complications in our favor—and since Black is missing the queen, we wish to avoid further simplifying exchanges that favor White.

make_move f6d5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board setup, one move to consider is using the knight on b3 to capture the pawn on d2. In standard chess notation this move is written as “b3d2.” This capture not only wins you a pawn but also exchanges your knight for white’s knight (once white recaptures on d2 with the knight from b1), which helps diminish white’s slight material edge.

When I evaluate alternatives such as moving the bishop or a pawn move, they seem less forcing. The bishop from c5 has options like moving to d4 or even capturing on a3, yet those moves don’t gain material immediately and could allow white additional counterplay. Similarly, pawn moves or shifting the rook don’t meet the same active objective.

Thus, my chosen move is:

make_move b3d2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one idea is to develop the dark‐squared bishop with tempo. Notice that the bishop on e7 can swing down along the long diagonal. In particular, moving it to b4 (i.e.  e7b4) puts the bishop on the diagonal b4–c3–d2–e1. Since White’s knight sits on c3, it becomes pinned against the king on e1. (If the knight were to move, it would expose the king to check, and capturing it later may win material.) 

Thus, a strong candidate move is:

 make_move e7b4

This develops a piece, creates a tactical threat against White’s pinned knight on c3, and increases control over key central squares.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one strong option is to use your f2‐pawn. It’s sitting one step away from the promotion rank (remember, for Black the back rank is row 1). By advancing the pawn from f2 to f1 and promoting (usually to a queen), you not only gain decisive extra firepower but also deliver an immediate check along the 1st rank (since your new queen on f1 will cover the entire row, including the white king’s d1 square).

Thus, I choose the move:

make_move f2f1q

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board layout, one urgent issue is that white’s bishop sitting on g5 is attacking our queen on e7 along the diagonal (g5–f6–e7–d8). We must neutralize that threat immediately. One solid way to do this is by interposing a defender along that diagonal. Notice that our pawn on f7 (at square f7) can advance one square forward to f6, landing on the square f6 (which is currently empty) and blocking the bishop’s line of sight to our queen on e7.

This move (f7 to f6) not only immediately interrupts the dangerous diagonal but avoids having to move the queen into less attractive territory. (If we were to move the queen instead, she could still be vulnerable to tactics and might lose coordination.) 

Thus, I recommend the move:

make_move f7f6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board’s layout, one critical issue is that the black knight on d2 is directly exposed on the d‐file. (Recall that white’s queen sits on d3, making d2 a “hot” square.) Moving the knight may be risky—since almost every destination (c4, e4, b3, f3, b1, f1) is also covered by the queen—but one idea stands out.

If Black plays …Nf3 (i.e. moving the knight from d2 to f3), then white faces a dilemma: 

• If white tries to capture it with the queen (Qxf3), then Black can recapture with the rook (Rxf3). Because the rook on f8 can swing down the f‑file (the squares between f8 and f3 are clear), this nets white’s queen for a knight—a disastrous exchange.

• To avoid that, white’s best response is likely to recapture on f3 with the pawn (g2×f3). Although Black “sacrifices” a knight for a pawn in that case (a net loss of about two points), Black was already ahead in material and this capture wrecks white’s kingside pawn shield.

Thus, …Nf3 sets a tactical trap forcing white to choose between an immediate blunder (losing the queen) or damaging their own structure. In UCI notation the move is:

make_move d2f3

I’ll now play 1... Nf3.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one idea stands out for Black. Notice that the white rook is the only piece keeping watch over the d‑file (especially the d7–d8 blockade that prevents the dangerously advanced white pawn on d7 from promoting). If we can force the rook off d1—even temporarily—then our rook on d8 could later capture that pawn. One way to nudge the rook is by improving the position of our pawn on c3. Moving it one step down to c2 (that is, c3 to c2) does two things:
 
• It continues to hold its place on the board while advancing closer to promotion.
• More importantly, once on c2, it “threatens” the d1 square via its normal diagonal capture pattern (remember, Black’s pawns move downward, so from c2 its capture targets are b1 and d1). Since the white rook is currently on d1 protecting the d‑file, Black’s move c3–c2 forces White to relocate the rook in order to avoid a nasty discovery. And if White is forced to leave the d‑file (or even reposition it inadequately), we might be able to come back later with our rook on d8 capturing the white pawn on d7—removing the passed pawn that’s only one step away from promotion.

Thus, as Black I choose to play:

 make_move c3c2

This is a forcing, proactive move that begins to create counter‑threats while not disturbing our key blockade on d8.
